This document describes the relevant and first ideas of technical and business metrics for Knowlestry Platfrom (in the development and operation mode on site)
Knowlestry Analytics is highly related to LLM/AI/Dev-Ops & resulting strategies for the product development and pricing strategies. 

Core Insight (What drives the metrics) 
--> AI costs are variable, behavioral, and compounding
--> Variance (not averages) breaks systems
--> Pricing = system control mechanism, not just monetization

So our metrics must:
---> Capture distribution, not averages
--> Reflect user behavior → cost causality
--> Track system complexity layers, not just tokens



A. Business Metrics (Pricing + Unit Economics) --> Revenue is behavioral, not fixed like SaaS
Some Most Important Business Metrics:
    – p95 cost per request
    – Contribution margin per user segment
    – Retry amplification factor
    – Peak concurrency cost
    – Heavy user cost concentration (%)

Pricing Model Effectiveness:
Hybrid-pricing (Pricing must shape behavior, not just capture value)
    – % users exceeding included quota
    – Subsidization ratio (heavy vs light users)

Revenue Metrics (Behavior-driven): 
    – Revenue per user (ARPU) — distribution, not average
    – Revenue per workflow
    – Overage revenue % (in hybrid pricing)
    – Revenue elasticity vs usage
    – Revenue per cost unit (e.g., per 1k tokens / workflow)

Risk & Sustainability Metrics
    – p95 cost vs price (unit economics safety margin)
    – Worst-day profitability
    – Concurrency shock resilience
    – Cost growth rate vs revenue growth rate

User Behavior Economics:
(Engagement can destroy margins if unmanaged)
    – Cost per user vs revenue per user (by segment)
    – Heavy user profitability
    – Exploration vs production usage ratio
    – Retry-driven usage (%)
    – “Waste” usage (low-value interactions)

Margin Metrics
(Track margin under stress, not just average)
    – Gross margin (%)
    – Contribution margin per user segment
    – Margin by percentile (p50 vs p95 users)
    – Margin under peak load scenario

    Cost of Goods Sold (Real AI COGS)

Break down COGS into:
    – Key Metrics: Fully-loaded cost per request (true COGS) --> COGS is not just model cost
    – Inference cost
    – Retrieval cost
    – Orchestration cost
    – Retry cost
    – Concurrency provisioning cost
    – Monitoring & evaluation cost

Some Practical Business Metrics: 
1. Economics
    – Fully-loaded cost per request
    – Revenue per request
    – Contribution margin (p50 / p95)
2. Risk
    – Cost variance (p95 / p50 ratio)
    – Retry amplification factor
    – Peak concurrency cost
3. Behavior
    – Cost per user distribution
    – Heavy user impact (% cost from top 5%)
    – Exploration vs production usage
4. System Efficiency
    – Calls per workflow
    – Context size growth
    – Model routing efficiency
5. Stability
    – Success rate
    – Retry rate
    – Latency under load









